\begin_layout Chapter
Classical Field Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intro/Stuff that will be useful in QFT:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Wave physics and many waves equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Theory of solitons.
 in 1d, solitons are kinks.
 2d are vortices.
 3d are monopoles and 4d instantons.
 Solitons are tightly related to symmetry breaking (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq44"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action (which is a functional) is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left[\phi\right]=\int_{M^{n}}\mathcal{L}\left[\phi\left(x\right)\right]d^{n}x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is the lagrangian that describes the system,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{L} & = & T-V
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is K.E.
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is P.E.), 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{n}$
\end_inset

 (Minkowsky space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) is the spactime and combines space dimensions (1,2,3) with time dimension
 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a coordinate of that spacetime).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action and the Lagrangian completely characterize the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
EOMS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How to reformulate functional minimization problems (like action) into PDEs:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\phi}S=\partial_{\phi}\mathcal{L}-\partial_{\mu}\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)}\right)=0\label{eq:eom1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}S$
\end_inset

 kind of means 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)\rightarrow\phi\left(x\right)+\partial\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
2nd order potential
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following action
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\int d^{n}x\left(\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)\left(\partial^{\mu}\phi\right)}_{K.E.}-\underbrace{\frac{m}{2}\phi^{2}\left(x\right)}_{P.E.}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a constant/parameter.
 The EOMs (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:eom1"

\end_inset

) become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\square+m^{2}\right)\phi\left(x\right)=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\square=\partial_{t}^{2}-\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain the EOMs we differentiated a quadratic function and so we obtained
 a linear PDE (?).The solutions are of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi=e^{ikx+i\omega t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Klein-Gordon theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 4th order (in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

) action (Klein-Gordon theory):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\int d^{n}x\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{\mu}\phi\partial^{\mu}\phi-\underbrace{\frac{\lambda}{4}\left(\phi^{2}-a^{2}\right)^{2}}_{P.E.}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(this is relevant to describing dynamics of Higgs-Boson).
 The potential is shown in the figure: 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ph205KleinGordonPotential.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Klein-Gordon potential and equilibrium points
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Eoms (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eom1"

\end_inset

) becomes that of Solitons with dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square\phi-\lambda\phi\left(\phi^{2}-a^{2}\right)=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(this is a cubic equation - called the Klein-Gordon equation - because we
 differentiated a quadratic Lagrangian and assume the K.E.
 part is obtained just like partial differentiating wrt to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 the K.E.
 term in the Lagrangian).
 If we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla_{x}^{2}\phi-\lambda\phi\left(\phi^{2}-a^{2}\right)=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{x}^{2}=d^{2}/dx^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that this is a symmetric equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow-\phi$
\end_inset

 but we will see that the soliton breaks the symmetry (it has to (??)).
 This equation turns out to have the solution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi\left(x\right)=\pm a\tanh\left(\sqrt{\frac{\lambda}{2}}ax\right)\label{eq:eq44}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and notice 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x=\pm\infty\right)=\pm a$
\end_inset

 and we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 migrates from one vacuum (which we define to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm a$
\end_inset

) to another vacuum.
 Such behavior defines a soliton.
 Also, the solution if not even like the EOM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sine-Gordon theory and Bogomolny Bound
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sine-Gordon theory:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\int d^{n}x\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{\mu}\phi\partial^{\mu}\phi-\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This gives the EOM:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square\phi+\sin\phi=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{tt}-\phi_{xx}+\sin\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
 This has soliton solutions that interpolate (alternate) between 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=2\pi n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 (these are the minima of the potential).
 The trick of solving such soliton equations is the Bogomolny Bound:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & = & T+V\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial_{t}\phi\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial_{x}\phi\right)^{2}+\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(where we consider that the K.E.
 is the part that contains derivatives) where each term is positive (adding
 contributions to 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 - trying to find minimum).
 Assume that we have a single kink that moves from 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi m$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\left(m+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The potential will look like: 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ph205SineGordonPotential.png
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sine-Gordon equation and assumed behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & \geq & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\left(\frac{1}{2}\phi_{x}^{2}+\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right)\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\left[\frac{1}{2}\phi_{x}^{2}+2\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right]dx\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\left(\frac{1}{2}\left[\phi_{x}\pm2\sin\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right]^{2}\mp2\sin\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\underbrace{\phi_{x}}_{\frac{d\phi}{dx}}\right)dx\\
 & = & \left(\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\frac{1}{2}\left[\phi_{x}\pm2\sin\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right]^{2}\right)\pm\left.4\cos\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right|_{-\infty}^{\infty}\\
 & \geq & 8
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.4\cos\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right|_{-\infty}^{\infty}=8
\end{equation}

\end_inset

because we assumed that the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 moves from one stable equilibrium point: 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi m$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

 to another stable equilibrium point: 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\left(m+1\right)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

In order to saturate the bound (i.e.
 to have 
\begin_inset Formula $E=8$
\end_inset

) we have a 1st order equation (BPS equations)*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\frac{1}{2}\left[\phi_{x}\pm2\sin\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right]^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive so it's contributions can only add to the energy
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{x}\pm2\sin\frac{\phi}{2}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 increases then (direction that we move from one vacuum to another) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{x}-2\sin\frac{\phi}{2}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We then obtin that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int dx=\int\frac{d\phi}{2\sin\frac{\phi}{2}}=\log\tan\left(\frac{\phi}{4}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and then we invert to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi=4\arctan e^{x-x_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This solution lends itself to interpreting 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 as a particle: it is localized (arctan has an abrupt change - a kink- over
 a narrow window) and has a center of mass given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 (this is the center of the region in which the kink is localized).
 With this solution it can be verified that 
\begin_inset Formula $E=8$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Chern-Simons theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\frac{k}{4\pi}\int_{M^{3}}Tr\left(AdA+A\wedge A\wedge A\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{3}$
\end_inset

 is a 3d spacetime, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the gauge 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and d and 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

 are differential geometry operators.
 EOMs will not be linear because the lagrangian is not quadratic.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial S}{\partial A}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

implies that ('Euler Lagrange equations)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{A}\equiv dA+A\wedge A=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $dA$
\end_inset

 is the magnetic field and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the field strength.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Yang-Mills theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left[A\right]=Im\tau\int Tr\left(F_{A}\wedge F_{A}+iF_{A}\wedge*F_{A}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Im\tau>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\theta/2\pi+4\pi i/g^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is called the coupling constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Quantum Field Theory (QFT)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast with classical field theory, QFT uses functionals (such as the
 action) directly rather than EOMs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Partition function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the particle-wave duality (that occurs like for example in the
 double slit experiment - 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Doubleslit3Dspectrum.gif
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - for electrons).
 The wave continuous part will help us calculate probabilities for the discrete
 entity: the particle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem of calculating probabilities relies on the fundamental ingredient
 of the partition function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=\int_{\mbox{possible fields}}\mathcal{D}\phi e^{-S\left[\phi\right]/\hbar}.\label{eq:ph205 partition qft}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 is very small, we can often approximately do this integral in the saddle
 point approximation (we find configurations to satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}S\left[\phi\right]=0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another fundamental ingredient is the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

, which can relay to us information (analogy given: thermometer), e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(x\right)=\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{k}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, etc ...
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 are combinations of basic building blocks like the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 We can have also more complicated non-local operators such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}=Tr_{R}Holy\left(A\left(x\right)\right),$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 characterizes a knot (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 is a function of not just one point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Analogy between stat Mechanics and QFT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two types of randomness appear in physics:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Quantum, when certain parameters are in the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

.
 There will be a characteristic partition function: 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:ph205 partition qft"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Thermal, with the characteristic parameter given by 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\mbox{Temperature}=\beta^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In statistical mechanics, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\sum_{\mbox{all configurations}}e^{-\beta E}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\beta E}$
\end_inset

 being the statistical weight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ising Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma=\pm1,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which characterizes spins on a lattice - to every point in space and time,
 a value is assigned.
 We can interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 as a field.
 We need to write down an action to describe the system.
 The analog of action in stat mechanics is the energy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=-J\sum_{\left\langle i,j\right\rangle \mbox{ nearest neighbors}}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j}-H\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is a good model for magnets if 
\begin_inset Formula $J>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
1D Ising Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume a circular configuration of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 spins with periodic conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}=\sigma_{i+N}$
\end_inset

.
 We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Z & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\exp\left(\beta J\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j+1}+\beta H\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be solved as we have a local interaction (interaction the same
 wherever we look at it) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of QFT, locality is a powerful concept and means that we
 have translational invariant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve it, define the 
\emph on
transfer matrix
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
T & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
e^{\beta\left(J+H\right)} & e^{-\beta J}\\
e^{-\beta J} & e^{\beta\left(J-H\right)}
\end{array}\right)\\
 & = & \left\{ \braket{\sigma|T|\sigma^{'}}\right\} 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and it specifies all possible values of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{\sigma|T|\sigma^{'}}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, we can rewrite the partition function to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Z & = & Tr\left(T^{N}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{N}}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 can be calculated to be 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{\pm}=e^{\beta J}\left[\cosh\left(\beta H\right)\pm\sqrt{\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)+e^{-4\beta J}}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 in diagonal form, ew have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Z & = & Tr\left(T^{N}\right)\\
 & = & \lambda_{+}^{N}+\lambda_{-}^{N}\approx\lambda_{+}^{N}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $N\gg1$
\end_inset

 and because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{+}>\lambda_{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Operators in the context of the Ising Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One legitimate choice of an operator (no unique choice) is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}=\sigma_{i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \mathcal{O}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle \sigma_{i}\right\rangle =\frac{1}{Z}\sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\sigma_{i}e^{-\beta E}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{Z}Tr\left(T^{N}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{\sinh\left(\beta+1\right)}{\sqrt{\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)+e^{-4\beta J}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the matrix 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 reflects the possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Tr\left(T^{N}\right) & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{N}}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
? & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{N}}\sigma_{2}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For simplicity, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}=\sigma_{2}$
\end_inset

, then we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{\sigma_{2}}\sigma_{2}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}} & = & \left[T\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)T\right]_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{3}}.\\
 & \equiv & \left(TGT\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{3}},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we defined 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
G & \equiv & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
1=\sigma_{1} & 0\\
0 & -1=\sigma_{2}
\end{array}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(T\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)T\right)_{ab} & = & \sum_{i}T_{ai}\left(GT\right)_{ib}\\
 & = & \sum_{ij}T_{ai}G_{ij}T_{jb}\\
 & = & \sum_{ij}T_{ai}\sigma_{i}\delta_{ij}T_{jb}\\
 & = & \sum_{i}T_{ai}\sigma_{i}T_{ib}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{N}}\sigma_{2}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...=Tr\left(T^{l}GT^{k}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are some integers.
 Using the cyclic property of the trace 
\begin_inset Formula $Tr\left(T^{l}GT^{k}\right)=Tr\left(GT^{k+l}\right)=Tr\left(GT^{N}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Compute the correlation function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and it measures the (degree of) order of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Perturbation theory (Feynmann diagrams)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In QFT, can rarely compute the partition function exactly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To do so, first decompose the action in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=S_{free\mbox{(i..e quadratic)}}+S_{interaction}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S_{interaction}$
\end_inset

 will often depend on small parameters of the theory, which allow us to
 carry out a perturbation calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
As an example, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left[A\right]=\int\underbrace{AdA}_{S_{free}}+\underbrace{\frac{2}{3\sqrt{k}}A^{3}}_{S_{interaction}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Moreover, we can take 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, which will give us a small parameter and will allow us to do a nice perturbati
on.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 is the 'nice' perturbative limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Take (and assume space consists of one point, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{n}=M^{0}$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\underbrace{m^{2}\phi^{2}}_{S_{free}}+\underbrace{\delta m^{2}\phi^{2}}_{S_{int}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the second term is a small correction to the first.
 Since we are working in 0d, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\mathcal{D}\phi=\int d\phi$
\end_inset

 and so we have that (
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=1$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=\int\mathcal{D}\phi e^{-S^{'}\left[\phi\right]=-m^{2}\phi^{2}}=\frac{\sqrt{\pi}}{m}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In our example, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Z & = & \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{\left(m^{2}+\delta m^{2}\right)}}\\
 & = & \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{m}}\left(1+\frac{\delta m^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)^{-1/2}\\
 & = & \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{m}}\left(1-\frac{1}{2}\frac{\delta m^{2}}{m^{2}}+\frac{3}{8}\left(\frac{\delta m^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)+...\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

For the simple case of 
\begin_inset Formula $S=m^{2}\phi^{2}$
\end_inset

, using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:ph205 green simple sol"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1/m^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analysis of the free part of the action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square G\left(x,y\right)=\delta\left(x-y\right),\label{eq:ph205 green simple}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the green's function and will turn out to be the 2-point correlation
 function (in the example of the Ising model, it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

).
 It is called the propagator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use the Fourier transform: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(p\right)=\int dxe^{ipx}f\left(x\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $\square G\left(x,y\right)=\delta\left(x-y\right)$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:ph205 green simple sol"

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(p^{2}+m^{2}\right)G\left(p\right) & = & 1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G\left(p\right)=\frac{1}{p^{2}+m^{2}}.\label{eq:ph205 green simple sol}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Notation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
This course uses the Einstein summation convention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is an abbreviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x^{\mu}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Contractions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{\mu\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{n}}B^{\mu\beta_{1}...\beta_{n}}=A_{\mu\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{n}}B_{\nu\beta_{1}...\beta_{n}}g^{\mu\nu},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}g^{\nu\lambda}=\delta_{\mu}^{\,\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
g_{\mu\nu} & = & \left(\begin{array}{cccc}
-1\\
 & 1\\
 &  & 1\\
 &  &  & 1
\end{array}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

